Targeting A Housing Subsidy

Yingxue Ou

Nov 2,2022

1 Introduction

This project aims to help the Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) target household who qualify for a home tax credit program and maximum the revenue that brought by those qualified households. Given a random sample of records with households age, jobs and marital etc., variables that might associated with their qualifications of home tax credit, a logistic regression model is generated to predict individuals will enter the program or not. As the cost/benefit of each individuals in confusion metrics can be calculated, the prediction results will be used to inform a cost/benefit analysis.

3 Data Exploration

In this section, the data is explored by visualizing correlation between y and the predictive features. As for the dependent variable y is binary, with two possible outcomes, it is better to plot features grouped by y which exhibit significant differences across the yes or no outcomes.

3.1 Feature importance

Figure 3-1 plots the mean for 7 continuous features grouped by y. It seems that the age, cons.conf.idx, cons.price.idx and spent_on_repairs have no influence in households choice of whether to enter the program or not. While, contacts with lower US inflation rate or unemployment rate, or who were contacts before this campaign for this ind. tend to enter the program.

3.3 Feature transformations

For there are too many categories in education and month, I create two variables Education and Season to store the reclassify results of education and month. Moreover, I classify pdays and age to use categorical variables rather than continuous variable.

Subsidy <- 
  Subsidy %>%
  # Education reclassify
  mutate(
    Education = case_when(education == "basic.9y"|education == "basic.4y"|education == "basic.6y" ~ "basic",
                                   education == "high.school" ~ "highschool",
                                   education == "university.degree" ~ "university",
                                   education == "professional.course" ~ "professional",
                                   education == "unknown" ~ "unknown",
                                   education == "illiterate" ~ "illiterate"
      )
 ) %>%
  # Month reclassified to season
  mutate(
    Season = case_when(
      month == "dec"|month == "jan"|month=="feb" ~ "winter",
      month == "mar"|month == "apr"|month=="may" ~ "spring",
      month == "jun"|month == "jul"|month=="aug" ~ "summer",
      month == "sep"|month == "oct"|month=="nov" ~ "fall"
    )
  ) %>%
  # Previous reclassify
   mutate(
    Contact = case_when(
      pdays == 999 ~ "No Contact",
      pdays < 7 ~" One week",
      pdays >= 7 &pdays <14 ~" Two weeks",
      pdays >= 15 &pdays <21 ~" Three weeks",
      pdays >= 22 ~" More than three weeks"
    )
  ) %>%
  # Age reclassify
  mutate(
    Age = case_when(
      age >= 18 & age < 25 ~"Gen Z",
      age >= 26 & age < 41 ~"Millenials",
      age >= 42 & age < 57 ~"Gen X",
      TRUE ~ "Boomer"
    )
  )

4 Regression Model

In this section, I will create Logistic regression model which is based on Maximum Likelihood Estimation. The logistic regression is estimated with glm function, in code chunks below, features will be delected by select operation in glm.

4.1 Split train/test set

Firstly, I partition data into a 65/35 training and test set (p = 0.65) and named them as SubsidyTrain and SubsidyTest.

set.seed(3456)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(Subsidy$y, p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)
SubsidyTrain <- Subsidy[ trainIndex,]
SubsidyTest  <- Subsidy[-trainIndex,]

4.2 Create a logistic regression model

Here I run model named as SubsidyModel1 with the dependent variable CreditNumeric and I used all variables before transformation in the regression.

SubsidyModel1 <- glm(CreditNumeric ~ .,
                  data=SubsidyTrain %>% 
                    dplyr::select(-X, -y, -y_numeric, -Education, -Season, -Contact, -Age),
                  family="binomial" (link="logit"))

It is important that evaluating a Logistic regression model can predict correctly or not.

First, Psuedo R Squared of two regression models are presented which could be helpful for quickly comparing different model specifications and feature selection. The McFadden of the first model is 0.2199889 which is slightly higher than the second model, that is, the first model is better.

4.5 Cross-Validation

This section performs cross-validation to two models using the caret::train function, respectively. The three metrics in the cvFit output are for mean AUC, Sensitively, and Specificity across 100 folds. And cvFit$resample joins data frame with goodness of fit for each 100 folds and plots the distribution as a small multiple plot(Figure 4-1 and 4-2).

The tighter each distribution is to its mean, the more generalizable the model. Both models generalizes well with respect to Specificity - the rate it correct predicts No Credit( the true negatives ). But they do not generilize as well with repect to Sensitively - the rate it correctly predicts Credit ( true positives ), model 2 even worse.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100, classProbs=TRUE, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary)

cvFit <- train(y ~ .,
                  data=Subsidy %>% na.omit()%>%
                    dplyr::select(-X, -CreditNumeric, -y_numeric, -Education, -Season, -Contact, -Age), 
                method="glm", family="binomial",
                metric="ROC", trControl = ctrl) # AUC = ROC

5 Make prediction

To prediction for SubsidyTest is a better approach to goodness to fit. First, I created a data frame of test set probabilities, testProbs, which includes both the observed households choices about whether to receive the credit or not and predicted probabilities for each observation. This predictions are the estimated probabilities of taking credit for the out-of-sample subjects. I will compare them to the observed outcome.

testProbs <- data.frame(Outcome = as.factor(SubsidyTest$CreditNumeric),
                        Probs = predict(SubsidyModel2, SubsidyTest, type= "response"))

head(testProbs)
##    Outcome      Probs
## 5        0 0.08098784
## 6        0 0.18708537
## 9        0 0.03876598
## 10       0 0.04963056
## 13       0 0.05430184
## 15       0 0.15116818

Figure 5-1 shows the distribution of predicted probabilities (x-axis) for receiving the credit or not, recoded as 1 and 0(y-axis), respectively. If the regression model was very predictive, the hump of predicted probabilities for Credit would around 1 on the x-axis, while the predicted probabilities for No credit would cluster around 0. 6 ROC curve

The code block below uses the plotROC and ggplot packages to create a ROC curve for the SubsidyModel2.

The y-axis of the ROC curve (Figure 6-1) shows the rate of true positives (correctly predicted will receive credit) for each threshold from 0.01 to 1. The x-axis shows the rate of false positives (predicted will receive credit and household didnt) for each threshold.

Follow the y-axis to about 0.6 and then across to the orange curve. According to the ROC Curve, a threshold that predicts Credit correctly 60% of the time, will predict Creidt incorrectly >10% of the time. Moving from a 60% to a 90% true positive rate dramatically increases the false positive rate.

7 Cost benefit analysis

7.1 Generating costs and benefits

Our goal is to target those household who will receive the credit. Assuming the model successfully predicts household will take the credit, and assuming a 2,850 dollars will be allocated to each household as marketing allocation. Given the new targeting algorithm, 25% of these households will receive 5,000 dollars credit at last while 75% will give up after receiving marketing allocation. According to evaluation by academic research in Philadelphia, houses that transacted after the credit sold 10,000 dollars higher on average.

Revenue and cost for each confusion metric can be explained and calculated as below:

<1>True Positive: Predicted correctly homeowner would enter credit program; allocated the marketing resources, and 25% ultimately achieved the credit. \(Revenue = (10000 - 2850 - 5000 + 56000) * count * 0.25 - (2850) * count *0.75\)

<2>True Negative: Predicted correctly homeowner would not take the credit, no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated. \(Cost = 0 * count\)

<3>False Positive: Predicted incorrectly homeowner would take the credit; allocated marketing resources; no credit allocated. \(Cost = 2850 * count\)

<4>False Negative: We predicted that a homeowner would not take the credit but they did. These are likely homeowners who signed up for reasons unrelated to the marketing campaign. Thus, we 0 out this category, assuming the cost/benefit of this is $0. \(Revenun = 0 * count\)

With equations above, cost benefit analysis for each confusion metrics is calculated in table below.

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs %>%na.omit()%>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Revenue =
                case_when(Variable == "True_Negative"  ~ Count * 0,
                         Variable == "True_Positive"  ~ ((10000 - 2850 - 5000 + 56000) * Count * 0.25 - (2850) * Count *0.75),
                         Variable == "False_Negative" ~ 0 * Count,
                         Variable == "False_Positive" ~ (-2850) * Count)) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "We correctly predicted won't receive credit",
              "We correctly predicted will receive credit",
              "We predicted won't receive credit and household received",
              "We predicted will receive credit and household didn't")))

kable(cost_benefit_table,
       caption = "Cost/Benefit Table") %>% kable_styling()
Cost/Benefit Table
Variable Count Revenue Description

True_Positive 30 372000 We correctly predicted will receive credit
False_Negative 126 0 We predicted wont receive credit and household received
False_Positive 12 -34200 We predicted will receive credit and household didnt

The next step of the cost/benefit analysis is to calculate the total Revenue across confusion metrics for each threshold.

whichThreshold[is.na(whichThreshold)] <- 0

whichThreshold_revenue <- 
whichThreshold %>% 
    group_by(Threshold) %>% 
    summarize(Revenue = sum(Revenue),
              Total_Count_of_Credits = sum(Total_Count_of_Credits))

8 Conclusion

The goal for this project is to help HCD targeting qualified home owners and maximize revenue by reducing the cost of marketing allocated on home owners who might not receive credit.

In conclusion, I dont recommend this model to be put into production. To figure out household who will receive credit, Sensitivity is an important indicator. The higher Sensitivity, the better the model is at predicting Credit. However, Sensitivity of the model is only 0.19 means that the model does not have convincing prediction ability.

The most possible reason for this result is that the training data set does not contain too much data which y = yes. Another possible reason is that there is little correlation between the variables and the independent variable, for their P-values indicate that the correlation is not significant.

Given that there is only 25% of contacted eligible homeowners receive the credit, which is relatively low rate, improving the response rate of marketing materials is another important method to boost revenue. According to Figure 3-1, 3-2 and 3-3, households who are contacts before this campaign, with lower unemployment rate at time of campaign, full time resident in Philadelphia tend to receive credit at last. And household previously contacted by cellular also tend to receive. So prioritizing contact with homeowners who meet the above criteria may help improve response rates.
